            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ilya Abramov\u2019s world began in the grey, concrete uniformity of 1980s Minsk. The son of an engineer father and a literature-teacher mother, his childhood was colored by the stark lines of Soviet architecture and the rich, imagined worlds of his mother\u2019s books. The collapse of the USSR was a chaotic yet exhilarating prelude to the family\u2019s emigration in the late 1990s. They settled in San Francisco\u2019s Richmond District, a foggy enclave that felt both foreign and strangely familiar with its own large Russian-speaking community.\n\nWhile grappling with English, Ilya found his voice in the universal language of visual art. He enrolled at San Francisco State University, earning a Bachelor's in Graphic Design, a field that satisfied both his innate artistic drive and his inherited appreciation for structure and function. His career path was a meticulous, steady climb, moving from junior roles to his current position as a Senior Exhibit Designer at the California Academy of Sciences. Here, he masterfully blends the bold, structuralist aesthetics of his youth with the interactive, organic forms required to showcase the natural world.\n\nNow 42, Ilya\u2019s life is one of quiet intention. He lives alone in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, just blocks from his parents. His daily routine is a comforting ritual: a walk to a Russian bakery for coffee and pastries, followed by a 2.5-mile MUNI ride on the 5-Fulton that cuts directly through Golden Gate Park to his office. He finds a deep sense of peace in the park\u2019s foggy mornings, a perfect backdrop for contemplative thought.\n\nThough reserved, Ilya maintains a small, tight-knit circle of friends\u2014a mix of fellow \u00e9migr\u00e9s and San Francisco natives. He\u2019s navigating single life after a long-term relationship ended two years prior, a turning point that refocused him on his personal and creative ambitions. His dream isn't about wealth, but legacy. He aspires to lead the design of a landmark exhibit, one that will be remembered for decades. On his own time, he works on a personal project: a series of digital illustrations based on the Slavic folktales his mother read to him in Minsk, a quiet tribute to the origins that continue to shape his unique vision of the world."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the first taxi ride from SFO, sixteen and utterly silent. The air, thick with salt and damp he\u2019d never known, smelled green. Outside, the world wasn't grey concrete but a blur of pastel houses with ornate windows, all softened by a milky fog. It felt like driving into a dream\u2014unreal, untethered. He saw the Cyrillic letters on a deli in the Richmond and felt a pang of both relief and profound loss. That moment wasn't about arrival; it was the quiet, dizzying realization that Minsk was now a memory.\n\n2.\nIn his high school art class, the assignment was \u201chome.\u201d While others drew the Golden Gate Bridge, Ilya sketched the severe, repeating rectangles of his Minsk apartment block from memory. His teacher paused, studying the stark, powerful lines. \u201cThis has a point of view,\u201d she said simply. The words landed like a key turning in a lock. For the first time, his past wasn't something to overcome but a unique lens. That quiet praise gave him permission to see his history not as a wound, but as a style.\n\n3.\nYears later, installing a new section of the Steinhart Aquarium, he had a moment of clarity. He was positioning a massive, fabricated coral structure against the stark, minimalist support grid he had designed. He saw it then: the rigid, structuralist aesthetic of his youth was the necessary skeleton for the vibrant, organic chaos of the reef. It was Minsk holding up San Francisco. That fusion became his signature, a deep professional satisfaction that felt like making peace between the two halves of his life.\n\n4.\nThe first Sunday after his breakup, the silence in his apartment was an accusation. He felt adrift, his future suddenly a blank page. On impulse, he pulled out his tablet, not to distract himself, but to work. He began sketching the Firebird, a creature from the tales his mother read. The intricate digital feathers became a meditation. In those quiet, focused hours, he realized his ambition wasn't tied to another person. His legacy would be his own, built from the stories that had shaped him from the very beginning.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on his morning walk through Golden Gate Park, the fog was so dense it swallowed all sound except the drip of water from eucalyptus leaves. He stopped, holding his warm coffee from the bakery, and watched the ghostly white dome of the Conservatory of Flowers emerge from the mist. It was a perfect, peaceful composition of nature and structure. He felt no longing for another place, no restlessness. Just a deep, quiet sense of belonging. This was his landscape now. He was home."
